The morphology and chemical bonding states of FTO films directly affect their electrical and optical properties. The morphology and chemical bonding states of the FTO films were simultaneously engineered by introducing a CQD thin film as an interfacial layer during USPD. Fig. 1
                     a shows the absorbance variation of the CQD aqueous dispersion in the range of 200−700 nm. The CQD aqueous dispersion exhibited two specific peaks at ∼207 and ∼333 nm, which correspond to the π-π* transition of graphitic carbon and n-π* transition of carbonyl groups in the CQDs, respectively [13]. The presence of these specific peaks can be ascribed to the strong absorbance of the individual nanoparticles without aggregates, which demonstrates the high dispersibility of the CQDs in water. The aqueous dispersibility of the CQDs is endowed by the abundant hydrophilic functional groups on the CQD surface. Moreover, the CQD dispersion exhibited strong blue-emitting fluorescence under UV light radiation compared with that under visible light radiation, which is due to the intense electron transition at discrete energy levels of the ultra-small nanoparticles (see the inset photographs in Fig. 1a). This fluorescence characteristic of the aqueous CQD dispersion supports the formation of quantum-sized carbon dots with abundant surface hydrophilic functional groups. Meanwhile, HR-TEM is a straightforward method for signifying the synthesis of CQDs. Fig. 1b shows an HR-TEM image of water dispersion by CQDs, where most particles exhibited quantum-sized spherical carbon dots (average size of ∼4.7 nm) with a lattice spacing of ∼0.23 nm, which is the typical d-spacing of graphite [14]. The exceptional aqueous dispersibility with blue-emitting fluorescence of the CQDs and their uniform distribution indicate the synthesis of CQDs abundant in surface functional groups. Fig. 1c shows actual photographs of the 1CQD/glass, 2CQD/glass, and 3CQD/glass used in the substrates following USPD. To elucidate CQD thin film morphology, SEM and AFM images were observed (Fig. 2
                     ). All CQD thin films exhibited homogeneous distribution of CQD particles without specific aggregates, which may lead to amicable interface engineering of the top-layered FTO films during USPD (Fig. 2a). Especially, sub-nano root mean square roughness (Rrms) of all CQD films function as an effective interfacial under-layer for FTO deposition (Fig. 2b−d). This uniform thin-film materialization was enabled via ultrasonic spray coating, which generated homogeneous and fine CQD droplets measuring 1 µm or less. The uniformity of the interfacial CQD thin film may have induced complete effects on the simultaneous morphological and chemical structural engineering of FTO films during the USPD. In particular, 1CQD/glass and 2CQD/glass exhibited excellent visible transparencies of 94.8 % and 90.0 %, respectively, as evaluated by measuring the average transmittance in the 400−700 nm range (Fig. 1d). This transparency guarantees that the CQD thin film serves as an effective interfacial layer that does not deteriorate the transparency of the FTO TCEs.

Fig. 7
a−d present top-view SEM images that show the morphology of all the FTO films. As expected, the bare FTO featured pyramidal crystallites interlocked with smaller crystallites and most of the pyramidal crystallites measured ∼388.9−311.1 nm (Fig. 7a). Similarly, 1CQD/FTO featured interlocked pyramidal crystallites with slight surface densification (Fig. 7b). More importantly, 1CQD/FTO showed a significant size reduction in the pyramidal crystallites (∼281.5−194.4 nm) compared with the bare FTO. This crystallite size reduction may be ascribed to the unstable interfacial CQD thin film providing greater surface free energy than SiO2 (glass substrate), thereby accelerating the nucleation rate of atomized precursor droplets near the surface of the CQD thin film [23]. Meanwhile, 2CQD/FTO showed an accelerated reduction in the crystallite size to ∼243.7−163.4 nm while exhibiting a highly densified surface morphology as compared with the cases of the bare FTO and 1CQD/FTO (Fig. 7c). This remarkable densification with smaller crystallites was due to the synergistic effects of accelerated nucleation rate and (200) oriented crystal growth by the considerable CQD film thickness. 3CQD/FTO exhibited a slight increase in the pyramidal crystallite size (∼270.2−179.8 nm) owing to the limited nucleation and crystal growth caused by the excessive CQD film thickness (Fig. 7d). Additionally, cross-view SEM and AFM images of bare FTO and 2CQD/FTO demonstrate the (200) oriented crystal growth of 2CQD/FTO compared to the bare FTO (Fig. 8
). From the cross-view SEM images (Fig. 8a and b), 2CQD/FTO featured smooth surface morphology, which results from the (200) oriented crystal growth parallel to the glass substrate. Similarly, AFM image of 2CQD/FTO exhibited smooth surface morphology with lower Rrms (23.1 nm) compared to bare FTO (28.7 nm) (Fig. 8c and d). Bare FTO and 2CQD/FTO exhibited almost same film thickness of ∼356.2−489.5 nm, which removes possible thickness effect on electrical and optical properties of FTO films. Significantly, the smooth and dense surface morphology of 2CQD/FTO was due to the presence of the interfacial CQD thin film, which modulated the nucleation and crystal growth behaviors of atomized precursor droplets during USPD, as compared with the cases of the bare FTO.

Fig. 10
a shows the transmittance spectrum over a wide range of wavelengths (280−800 nm) for all the FTO TCEs. In the visible light range of 400−700 nm, the average transmittances exhibited by the bare FTO, 1CQD/FTO, 2CQD/FTO, and 3CQD/FTO were ∼83.6 %, ∼83.8 %, ∼85.9 %, and ∼82.4 %, respectively (Table 1
). The significant visible transmittance (> 83 %) indicated by all the FTO films suggests their applicability as transparent conducting films (TCFs). However, a slight increase in the visible transmittance was observed from the bare FTO to 2CQD/FTO, despite the presence of an interfacial CQD thin film. As revealed by the visible transmittance of each CQD/glass substrate (Fig. 1c and d), the presence of the CQD thin film under the FTO film had likely reduced the transmittance compared with that of the bare FTO. The slight enhancement in the visible transmittance of 2CQD/FTO demonstrated the effective engineering of the FTO film morphology toward a smooth surface with relaxed roughness, which maximized the transmissivity by minimizing light scattering and reflection. The optical band gap energies of all the FTO films were calculated as follows: (αhv)2 = K(hv − Eg)n, where α is the absorption coefficient, hv is the photon energy, K is a constant, and Eg is the optical band-gap energy [27]. According to the Beer-Lambert's law, α and light pathlength (d) have an exponential relation to transmitted intensity (I) and incident intensity (I0
) as follows: I = I0
e−

   αd
. Based on the equation, we obtained α for all FTO films by calculating following equation: α = ln(1/T) × 1/d, where T is transmittance. The T was measured by UV–vis spectroscopy and the d was counted as 7 × 10−4 m, which is the thickness of glass substrate. Band-gap widening occurred from the bare FTO (3.93 eV) to 2CQD/FTO (4.05 eV) (Fig. 10b) owing to the increase in the F-doping concentration, which shifted the absorption edge to higher energies in the conduction band (known as the Burstein-Moss shift) due to the interfacial CQD thin film effect [28]. By contrast, 3CQD/FTO showed a reduction in the band-gap energy owing to the relaxed F-doping and the impurity band formed near the conduction band by the excessive CQDs in the interface. Meanwhile, 2CQD/FTO showed an enhancement in the visible transmittance, which was endowed by the smooth surface morphology with the (200) orientation, thus demonstrating the availability of TCEs. Fig. 10c shows the electrical properties of all the FTO films, i.e., their carrier concentration, carrier mobility, and resistivity, obtained using the Hall-effect measurement system (Table 1). Considering that the resistivity and sheet resistance are determined by the carrier concentration and carrier mobility, 2CQD/FTO showed a significant decrease in resistivity (3.18 × 10−4 Ω∙cm) and sheet resistance (∼5.7 Ω/□) but an increase in the carrier concentration (7.65 × 1020 cm−3) and mobility (25.62 cm2/V∙s) as compared with the bare FTO (6.49 × 10−4 Ω∙cm, ∼11.8 Ω/□, 4.09 × 1020 cm−3, and 23.51 cm2/V∙s, respectively). The carrier concentration increase exhibited by 2CQD/FTO was derived from the enhanced F-doping and VO concentration, which generated additional free electrons. The enhanced carrier mobility exhibited by 2CQD/FTO was attributed to the highly preferred (200) orientation of the FTO film, which provided facile electron transfer pathways. As a result, 2CQD/FTO exhibited the best TCF properties with the lowest sheet resistance and highest visible transmittance compared to those of the bare FTO, 1CQD/FTO, and 3CQD/FTO (Fig. 10d). A figure of merit (ϕ) that considers both the optical and electrical properties was calculated using the following equation: ϕ = T10/Rsh, where T is the visible transmittance and Rsh is the sheet resistance of the FTO TCEs [29]. Based on the results, 2CQD/FTO showed the highest ϕ value (3.84 × 10−2 Ω−1) as compared with the bare FTO (1.41 × 10−2 Ω−1), 1CQD/FTO (1.82 × 10−2 Ω−1), and 3CQD/FTO (1.79 × 10−2 Ω−1) (Fig. 11
). This significant enhancement of transparent conducting performance in 2CQD/FTO is due to the effects of the optimized interfacial CQD thin film impacts as follows: (i) The smooth surface morphology maximizes visible light transmissivity by relaxing scattering and reflection centers at the film surface. (ii) The preferred (200) orientation with film densification provides facile electron transfer pathways, thus resulting in the enhanced electron mobility. (iii) The accelerated F-doping and increase in VO concentration generate additional free electrons, thus increasing the carrier concentration. Therefore, the introduction of a CQD thin film with abundant oxygen-containing functional groups as an interface layer during USPD can be an engineering technique for developing both the morphological and chemical structures of FTO films toward transparent conducting performance.
